  "opinion": "As a mechanic in Milan with a background that’s more hands-on than academic, I’ve seen how science gets talked about in my shop—mostly through fixing cars and understanding how engines work. The gender gap in science isn’t something I’ve seen up close in my own life, but I know it’s real. When I talk to people at the local football club or in my community, I hear stories about how girls and women are discouraged from pursuing science early on. My own parents, one with a bachelor’s and the other with only primary school education, taught me that science is for everyone, but they didn’t have the same opportunities they had. I’ve noticed that in many communities, especially in Italy, there’s a bias toward traditional roles—men in engineering, women in care work. It’s not just about gender; it’s about how we view what’s ‘possible’ for someone. The gap exists because society tells girls they’re not meant for math or physics, and boys are pushed to be ‘fixers’ from a young age. I think we should address it, but not with big, top-down policies that don’t consider the real-world context. Instead, we need small, local changes—like encouraging girls to join science clubs at school, or supporting women who want to study engineering through mentorship programs. My own experience as a mechanic shows that hands-on learning is powerful, and that’s where science starts. It’s not about changing the system overnight but building confidence in people who feel they don’t belong. In my community, we can start by having more conversations about what science means in everyday life—like how a car engine works or how to fix a leaky pipe. That’s where the real change begins, not in distant universities or government reports.",
